AGI - "The night spent well, the Pope slept and is resting >". It makes known the Vatican press room updating on the precarious health of the Holy Father.&nbsp;
Pope Francis "was awake and is continuing therapies". His "noise is good." They affirm Vatican sources that explain that the Pontiff eats regularly. &nbsp;
The same sources explain that&nbsp; Pope Francis "has no pain". The respiratory crises that brought "sofferences" to the Pontiff on Saturday, "are past". &nbsp;
The latest medical bulletin issued by the Vatican, published on Sunday, explains how the conditions "permanent criticism" and the complexity of the clinical picture imposes "that the prognosis remains reserved". The novelty that worries is the emergence of a kidney failure but, it explains, is "lieve", in the "initial" phase and "under control". Since Saturday evening there have also been no "last respiratory crisis", although "oxytherapy continues with high flow through nasal cannulas".
<h2>Spadaro: "Resign? He will decide before God"</h2>
&nbsp;"I was sorry to see forcedness, wrong interpretations, sometimes even attacks on the Pontiff in this condition. I think this is the moment of prayer, of waiting or the time to express 'good waves', as the Pope says when he addresses those who are not believer." Thus the Jesuit Antonio Spadaro, among the closest collaborators of Pope Francis, in an interview with Repubblica. Regarding the possibility of resignation, Father Spadaro recalls that "in one of his trips he clearly said that the Papacy is alive. The idea of renouncing the Petrine ministry, already mentioned in the past, appears as a weighted option if the energies were irreversible."
"The Pope - he continues - has always said that Benedict has opened a path and finds it possible that a Pope resigns to his ministry, but this will be verified on the basis of what will be in the coming days. This is not the time to talk about the so-called resignations, therefore. >However I want to point out that the decision would be the fruit of a weighted spiritual discernment before God, and not simply a problem of efficiency and physical power. The latter would be a worldly criterion, completely alien to the thought of the Pontiff."
<h2> From the hospital the appointments of bishops </h2>
Despite the precarious health conditions, Pope Francis shows himself in activity. From a series of bulletins spread by the Vatican Press Office you learn about the episcopal appointments. On Monday 24 February, the pontiff appointed Bishop of Vittorio Veneto (Treviso)> Rev. Riccardo Battocchio, of the clergy of the Diocese of Padua, until now Rector of the Almo Collegio Capranica in Rome.&nbsp;
Monsignor Camillo Cibotti, was appointed Bishop of the Diocese of Trivento> (Campobasso) and Bishop of the Diocese of Isernia-Venafro, joining the two offices in person Episcopi. He was also referred to as Coadjutor Bishop of the Diocese of Santos (Brazil) > Monsignor Joaquim Giovani Mol Guimaraes, transferring him from the Headquarters of Galtelli' and from the Office of Auxiliary of Belo Horizonte.
Finally, in the diocese of San Cristobal de la Laguna, Tenerife Reverend Eloy Alberto Santiago, until now Chancellor-General Secretary of the Diocese of Islas Canarias.&nbsp;

