AGI - Lawyer Giacomo Maj intends to ask tomorrow at the Court of Assisi in Bergamo that Moussa Sangare, 31-year-old Italian citizen of Malian origin, is subjected to a psychiatric examination to determine whether he is able to understand and want when, in the night between 29 and 30 July last year, killed Sharon Verzeni in Terno d'Isola.
&nbsp;
This will be the most important step of the first hearing of the judgment with the immediate rite at the expense of the young accused of voluntary murder aggravated by the futile motives, the premeditation and the handicapped defense for the crime that for a month kept the public alert waiting for the investigators to find the key to what appeared a puzzle. The bicycle killer was spotted through the cameras. The continuous inspections in the house where the bartender lived with the promised spouse Sergio Ruocco made suspect in his involvement, hypotheses completely swept away from the epilogue of the investigation.
&nbsp;
Shortly after midnight he went out alone with earphones, a habit, as Ruocco said, which he had taken in recent times because he wanted to lose a few pounds. By the time of his life for the knives received from Sangare in Via Castegnate, he clinged to a gate and managed to call the 118 saying, before he died: "He stabbed me." The story of Sangare, aspiring rapper living in a busy house, delinated a murder without motive: "I saw a girl with headphones watching the stars in the sky.
&nbsp;
I approached her from behind, put a hand on her shoulder and told her: "Sorry for what's about to happen." Sangare said that night was moved by a "feeling" and killed without a reason the person in which he came across, the one who, according to the evaluation of the gip, seemed more defenseless. Tomorrow they are expected in the classroom Bruno Verzeni, Sharon's father, mother Maria Teresa Previtali, civil parts with his sons Melody and Christopher, as well as Ruocco, all assisted by lawyer Luigi Scudieri.&nbsp;

